<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="165" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">
This cosmopolitan species is found in the epipelagic (0-200 m depth) and mesopelagic zones (200-500 m depth) of the Pacific, Indian and Atlantic Oceans (
<bibRefCitation author="Pierrot-Bults, AC" editor="Bone, Q" journalOrPublisher="Oxford Science Publications, New York" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" pagination="86 - 116" refId="B70" refString="Pierrot-Bults, AC, Nair, VR, 1991. Distribution patterns in Chaetognatha. In: Bone, Q, Kapp, H, Pierrot-Bults, AC, Eds., The Biology of the Chaetognaths. Oxford Science Publications, New York: 86 - 116" title="Distribution patterns in Chaetognatha." volumeTitle="The Biology of the Chaetognaths." year="1991">Pierrot-Bults and Nair 1991</bibRefCitation>
), the coastal area of Japan (Tosa Bay; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3800/pbr.9.176" author="Ohnishi, T" journalOrPublisher="Plankton &amp; Benthos Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" pagination="176 - 187" refId="B59" refString="Ohnishi, T, Ueda, H, Kuroda, K, 2014. Community structure and spatial distribution of chaetognaths in Tosa Bay on the temperate Kuroshio coast of Japan. Plankton &amp; Benthos Research 9 (3): 176 - 187, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3800/pbr.9.176" title="Community structure and spatial distribution of chaetognaths in Tosa Bay on the temperate Kuroshio coast of Japan." url="https://doi.org/10.3800/pbr.9.176" volume="9" year="2014">Ohnishi et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
) and the epipelagic zone (0-150 m depth) of the Korea Strait (
<bibRefCitation author="Park, JS" journalOrPublisher="The Korean Society of Oceanography" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" refId="B61" refString="Park, JS, 1970. The chaetognaths of Korean waters. PhD Thesis, Pukyong National University, Busan, South Korea." title="The chaetognaths of Korean waters. PhD Thesis, Pukyong National University, Busan, South Korea." year="1970">Park 1970</bibRefCitation>
). In this study, it was found in the epipelagic zone (0-110 m depth) of the northern East China Sea (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Sampling stations in Korean waters. Empty circles, sampling stations; filled circles, the stations where the chaetognaths were secured." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.80184.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/704185" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">1</figureCitation>
: stations KS08, nECS01 and nECS04).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="165" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">
This is used as an indicator species of warm currents in water surrounding Korea (
<bibRefCitation author="Park, JS" journalOrPublisher="The Korean Society of Oceanography" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" refId="B61" refString="Park, JS, 1970. The chaetognaths of Korean waters. PhD Thesis, Pukyong National University, Busan, South Korea." title="The chaetognaths of Korean waters. PhD Thesis, Pukyong National University, Busan, South Korea." year="1970">Park 1970</bibRefCitation>
). The temperature range in the sampling stations was 16.52-28.80 °C and the salinity range was 28.96-33.22 psu.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="165" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="165">
The transparent and flaccid body, star-shaped eye pigments and seminal vesicle morphology were consistent with those recorded in previous studies by 
<bibRefCitation author="Alvarino, A" journalOrPublisher="University of California, Scripps Institution of Oceanography" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" refId="B4" refString="Alvarino, A, 1967. The Chaetognatha of the NAGA Expedition (1959-1961): In the South China Sea and the Gulf of Thailand (Vol. 4). University of California, Scripps Institution of Oceanography" title="The Chaetognatha of the NAGA Expedition (1959 - 1961): In the South China Sea and the Gulf of Thailand (Vol. 4)." year="1967">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Alvariño">Alvarino</normalizedToken>
(1967)
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Nagasawa, S" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the Plankton Society of Japan" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" pagination="96 - 106" refId="B54" refString="Nagasawa, S, 1976. Identification of young chaetognaths based on the characteristics of eyes and pigmented regions. Bulletin of the Plankton Society of Japan 23: 96 - 106" title="Identification of young chaetognaths based on the characteristics of eyes and pigmented regions." volume="23" year="1976">Nagasawa (1976)</bibRefCitation>
. Two types of Korean 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Grassi" baseAuthorityYear="1881" class="Sagittoidea" family="Sagittidae" genus="Flaccisagitta" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Flaccisagitta enflata" order=" Aphragmophora" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" phylum="Chaetognatha" rank="species" species="enflata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">Flaccisagitta enflata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have been reported, a small type: 10-20 mm long and a large type: 20-28 mm long (
<bibRefCitation author="Park, JS" journalOrPublisher="The Korean Society of Oceanography" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" refId="B61" refString="Park, JS, 1970. The chaetognaths of Korean waters. PhD Thesis, Pukyong National University, Busan, South Korea." title="The chaetognaths of Korean waters. PhD Thesis, Pukyong National University, Busan, South Korea." year="1970">Park 1970</bibRefCitation>
). In this study, only the small type (&lt;20 mm) of 
<taxonomicName genus="F." lsidName="F. enflata" pageId="0" pageNumber="165" rank="species" species="enflata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="165">F. enflata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was collected. We observed seven specimens for CBE staining pattern: dorsomedian line, 12 dots; dorsolateral line,&gt; 150 dots; ambiguous lateral line, receptors on the lateral fin, 2 dots (easily damaged); anterolateral receptors on the caudal fin, 4 dots; posterior receptors on the caudal fin, 7 dots. The pattern of dorsomedian dots lined up behind the ventral ganglion and the pattern of dorsolateral dots intensively scattered ahead of ventral ganglion.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
